<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>Triglycerides as a Window Into Metabolic Health</h2>

  <p>Triglycerides are commonly discussed as a cardiovascular risk factor in the same breath as LDL cholesterol. This framing is accurate but undersells their significance as a metabolic marker. Elevated triglycerides are not just an independent cardiovascular risk factor &#8212; they are one of the most reliable indicators of insulin resistance, excess carbohydrate intake, and impaired fat metabolism that a standard blood panel provides.</p>

  <p>This matters because the conditions that drive triglycerides up &#8212; chronically elevated insulin, excess refined carbohydrate consumption, visceral adiposity, physical inactivity &#8212; are the same conditions that drive cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, and cognitive decline. Triglycerides are not merely a downstream cardiovascular risk marker; they are a readout of the entire metabolic environment.</p>

  <p>The good news is that triglycerides are among the most responsive biomarkers to intervention. Unlike ApoB or LDL, which often require months to shift meaningfully, triglycerides can fall 30&#8211;50% within weeks of dietary change. This makes them an unusually useful real-time feedback signal for assessing whether a metabolic intervention is working.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>Standard Reference Ranges vs. Longevity-Optimal Ranges</h2>

  <p>The current clinical classification of triglycerides identifies "normal" as below 150 mg/dL &#8212; a threshold based on the point at which cardiovascular and pancreatitis risk become clinically obvious. It does not represent metabolic optimality. The evidence consistently shows that fasting triglycerides above 80&#8211;100 mg/dL are associated with elevated risk even within the "normal" zone.</p>

