  <p>Calculate your ratio: divide fasting triglycerides (mg/dL) by HDL cholesterol (mg/dL). Both numbers are on any standard lipid panel. This single calculation often reveals more about actual cardiovascular risk than LDL cholesterol alone.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>What Raises Triglycerides &#8212; and How to Lower Them</h2>

  <p>Understanding the drivers gives a clear optimization roadmap. Triglycerides are highly responsive to lifestyle, making this one of the most actionable biomarkers in the longevity panel.</p>

  <h3>Primary drivers of elevated triglycerides</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Sugar and refined carbohydrate excess:</strong> The dominant driver. Sugar-sweetened beverages, sweets, refined grains, and ultra-processed foods provide a sustained flood of glucose and fructose that exceeds glycogen storage and drives hepatic fat synthesis.</li>
    <li><strong>Alcohol:</strong> Alcohol is metabolized almost exclusively in the liver, where it stimulates fatty acid synthesis and inhibits fatty acid oxidation &#8212; directly raising VLDL and triglycerides. Even moderate alcohol consumption (2&#8211;3 drinks per day) significantly elevates triglycerides in susceptible individuals.</li>
    <li><strong>Physical inactivity:</strong> Exercise increases muscle glycogen storage capacity and triglyceride clearance through lipoprotein lipase activity. Sedentary adults have reduced capacity to clear circulating triglycerides after meals.</li>
    <li><strong>Visceral adiposity:</strong> Visceral fat releases free fatty acids into the portal circulation, driving hepatic triglyceride synthesis and VLDL secretion independently of dietary intake.</li>
    <li><strong>Insulin resistance:</strong> Insulin normally suppresses hepatic VLDL secretion. When insulin resistance develops, this brake is lost and the liver produces VLDL continuously at a high rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Hypothyroidism:</strong> Thyroid hormones are required for LPL activity (the enzyme that clears triglycerides from the blood). Even subclinical hypothyroidism can meaningfully raise triglycerides.</li>
    <li><strong>Certain medications:</strong> Beta blockers, thiazide diuretics, corticosteroids, some antipsychotics, and oral estrogen (but not transdermal) can raise triglycerides.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Most effective interventions to lower triglycerides</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Eliminate sugar-sweetened beverages:</strong> The single highest-impact dietary change for most people. Soft drinks, fruit juices, energy drinks, and sweetened coffee drinks deliver concentrated fructose directly to the liver's fat synthesis pathway.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduce refined carbohydrates:</strong> White bread, pasta, crackers, chips, and packaged foods provide rapidly absorbed glucose that spills over into fat synthesis when consumed in excess of glycogen capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Aerobic exercise:</strong> Both acute exercise and chronic training increase lipoprotein lipase activity, the enzyme that clears triglycerides from the bloodstream. A single bout of aerobic exercise lowers post-meal triglycerides by 20&#8211;30%; regular training produces persistent baseline reductions.</li>
    <li><strong>Omega-3 fatty acids:</strong> EPA and DHA (from fish oil) at doses of 2&#8211;4 grams per day are one of the most consistently effective pharmacological interventions for hypertriglyceridemia, reducing triglycerides by 20&#8211;45% in clinical trials. The FDA has approved high-dose prescription omega-3 formulations (Vascepa, Lovaza) specifically for severe hypertriglyceridemia. Over-the-counter fish oil at 3&#8211;4 grams EPA+DHA is similarly effective at lower price.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduce or eliminate alcohol:</strong> Even cutting alcohol from daily to occasional use produces rapid, significant triglyceride reductions in most individuals.</li>
    <li><strong>Lose visceral fat:</strong> Any intervention that reduces abdominal fat reduces the continuous free fatty acid flux to the liver that drives VLDL overproduction.</li>
    <li><strong>Address hypothyroidism:</strong> If triglycerides are elevated and TSH is above the optimal range, treating hypothyroidism often normalizes triglycerides without additional dietary intervention.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>How to Test Triglycerides</h2>

  <p>Triglycerides are measured from a standard fasting blood draw and are included in every standard lipid panel. Fasting for 9&#8211;12 hours before the draw is required for an interpretable result &#8212; post-meal chylomicrons can raise triglycerides by 100+ mg/dL compared to the true fasting baseline.</p>

  <p>When reviewing your lipid panel, always note your HDL alongside your triglycerides and calculate the ratio yourself &#8212; labs rarely report it, yet it is often more informative than LDL alone.</p>

  <p>For a complete cardiovascular picture, pair triglycerides with <a href="/biomarkers/apob">ApoB</a> &#8212; the gold standard for atherogenic particle count. The combination of triglycerides, HDL, and ApoB gives a comprehensive view of both metabolic health and cardiovascular risk that far exceeds what LDL cholesterol alone provides.</p>

  <p>Testing frequency: annually as part of a comprehensive metabolic panel for most adults. If actively working to lower elevated triglycerides through dietary or lifestyle changes, a retest at 4&#8211;6 weeks provides useful early feedback given how quickly triglycerides respond.</p>
</section>

